What is APR?APR stands for Annual Percentage Rate. It's a measure used to compare the yearly cost of borrowing or earning money across different loans, mortgages, credit cards, etc. The APR includes not only the interest rate but also any additional fees or costs associated with the loan.

For example, if you're taking out a mortgage and the APR is 4%, that means the total annual cost of borrowing this money (including all fees) would be equivalent to an interest rate of 4%. 

It's important for consumers to understand APR because it provides a more complete picture of what they'll actually pay or earn over the course of a year.yes
